properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A band of snow is expected to move over Northwestern Ontario this morning from Eastern Manitoba and Northern Minnesota. The snow may be briefly mixed with ice pellets and freezing rain, especially near the Manitoba Border. Snow amounts of 4 to 8 cm appear likely across the region by this evening. Motorists should allow for extra time to reach their destination as untreated highways may become snow covered and slippery. This may be the largest snowfall so far this year across the area. Snow will gradually ease off tonight. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
Expires: 2021-01-15T03:14:40-00:00

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A cold front which tracked across southern Saskatchewan overnight has now moved into southwestern Manitoba. In its wake strong northwesterly winds in excess of 90 km/h are expected which together with falling snow will create blizzard conditions with zero visibilities in blowing snow. Over southeastern Saskatchewan and southwestern Manitoba blizzard conditions are expected but will gradually improve later this morning as the snow diminishes in intensity. However, strong northwesterly winds will persist maintaining blowing snow in the region throughout the day with the blowing snow not ending until Thursday evening. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A cold front tracking across Saskatchewan will make its way eastward towards the Manitoba boundary overnight. As it passes strong northwesterly winds in excess of 90 km/h together with falling snow will create blizzard conditions with zero visibilities in blowing snow. Conditions are expected to improve over western Saskatchewan towards midnight and south central Saskatchewan overnight. Over southeastern Saskatchewan and southwestern Manitoba blizzard conditions are expected to improve Thursday morning as the snow diminishes in intensity. However, strong northwesterly winds will persist maintaining blowing snow in the region throughout the day with the blowing snow not ending until Thursday evening. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant precipitation expected beginning Saturday night. Total snowfall: 15 cm or more for Northern New Brunswick. Total rainfall: 25 mm or more for areas near the Fundy coast. Locations: New Brunswick. Time span: Saturday night through to Sunday morning. Remarks: Snow is expected to spread across northern New Brunswick and rain across southern New Brunswick Saturday night. Snow and freezing rain are expected for central parts of the province Saturday night, changing to rain overnight. Conditions will begin to improve Sunday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A disturbance tracking across central Manitoba will spread heavy snow across northern Manitoba. properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Brief, intense snowfall is expected to develop. Under the snow squall, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow. The snowsquall watch has been replaced by a blizzard warning for south central and southeastern Saskatchewan. The snowsquall watch remains in effect for the Cypress Hills, Maple Creek and Shaunavon. Brief squalls of snow and wind are expected over region. Snow squalls, with brief near-zero visibilites in snow and blowing snow, will form in parts of southwestern Saskatchewan this evening. While a squall may only last less than an hour, whiteout conditions are likely with any squall that does occur. The potential for snow squalls will end overnight. ### Travel may be hazardous due to sudden changes in the weather. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for brief but intense bursts of heavy snow producing near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard near the Richardson mountains overnight tonight and Friday. Very strong easterly winds will develop near the Richardson mountains overnight as an intense frontal system approaches. Peak winds of 90 gusting 110 km/h can be expected early Friday morning. These winds will combine with loose snow on the ground to produce blizzard conditions through Friday afternoon. Conditions are expected to improve late Friday as the winds ease in the wake of the front. ### Travel is expected to be very difficult or impossible due to near-zero visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #YTStorm.
